{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":173,"record_hash":"sha256:f3a855b983aad5838d78b9ead951c38125655ffdd2914202d389972df62dade7","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:31:18.399Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: agent-trail.md\n@@\n ## Server-Side Metadata Fetch\n \n For public v1, the Forge server should be able to create an Agent Trail snapshot\n on demand by fetching GitMeta metadata for the repository referenced by the PR\n URL.\n+\n+This only works when `refs/meta/main` has actually been published to the public\n+GitHub repository. Forge's existing `but-sync` flow pushes metadata to private\n+code.storage workspace refs such as `refs/<client_id>/meta/*`; that does not\n+make metadata available to URL-replacement reviewers. Agent Trail v1 assumes\n+public metadata already exists and should show a missing-metadata state when it\n+does not. Publishing metadata to GitHub can be a later GitButler/GitMeta\n+distribution feature.\n@@\n Possible first flow:\n \n 1. parse the PR URL into forge, owner, repo, and PR number\n 2. fetch GitHub PR metadata through public-equivalent access and verify that the\n    repository and pull request are public/readable\n 3. reject fork pull requests for v1\n-4. create or refresh a server-side bare/cache checkout for the repository\n+4. create or refresh a server-side scratch/cache repository for the repository\n 5. fetch `refs/meta/main`\n 6. resolve the fetched metadata ref to an OID\n 7. run `but-agentlog` lookup/projection code against\n    the fetched repository metadata\n 8. generate an Agent Trail snapshot from the `but-agentlog` public/read\n@@\n Minimum cache behavior:\n \n - key cache entries by forge host and GitHub repository id; store owner/repo as\n   display aliases\n-- store a bare or otherwise server-safe checkout, not a working tree meant for\n-  edits\n+- store a scratch repository that is safe for GitMeta reads, not a working tree\n+  meant for edits. If the initial `but-agentlog` API still needs a non-bare\n+  repository, initialize a non-bare repo with no checkout and fetch only the\n+  metadata ref.\n - prefer an exact metadata fetch into the cache over a full repository clone\n - do not fetch normal refs in v1; GitHub PR metadata supplies title, base, head,\n   and head SHA\n@@\n - define initial guardrails for repository count, storage bytes, TTL/LRU\n   eviction, negative-cache TTLs, and per-IP/per-repo rate limits before this is\n   used broadly. Exact thresholds can be tuned while implementing.\n+- require a deployment target with writable local cache storage, `git`\n+  available, and the Rust projection helper bundled. If production is\n+  serverless with ephemeral filesystem or no process execution, either disable\n+  snapshot caching for that environment or move generation to a worker/service.\n@@\n Recommended split:\n \n-- Forge owns PR URL parsing, access checks, snapshot generation, caching, and UI\n+- Forge TypeScript owns PR URL parsing, GitHub public lookup, route/API\n+  responses, snapshot generation, caching, and UI\n - `git-meta-lib` or a small shared helper owns GitMeta transport/fetch details\n-- `but-agentlog` owns interpretation of GitButler agentlog keys and records\n+- the Forge Rust projection helper owns the process boundary and JSON transport\n+  between Next and Rust\n+- `but-agentlog` owns interpretation of GitButler agentlog keys and records,\n+  target construction, verified lookup, and the public/read projection\n \n If the metadata ref is missing or cannot be fetched, the page should show a\n clear empty state rather than treating the PR as having no agent work:\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:31:18.399Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}